# Document Delivery System (`@/lib/document-delivery`)

Sending files to a customer (or agent, or anyone) is a SINGLE concern in
this codebase. Every "Email this file" / "WhatsApp this file" / "Share
download link" flow goes through the same shared abstractions.

## Why this rule exists

Before the document-delivery extraction the same logic was duplicated
in 4+ places:

- `components/policies/tabs/WorkflowTab.tsx` — recipient resolution
- `components/policies/EmailUploadedFilesDialog.tsx` — PDF template loader
- `components/policies/WhatsAppUploadedFilesDialog.tsx` — PDF template loader
- `components/policies/tabs/DocumentsTab.tsx` — inline `wa.me` URL builders, `handleEmail` / `handleWhatsApp` handlers
- `app/api/presence/online/route.ts` — phone resolution (different shape, different fallback chain)

Each copy was slightly different (different keys, different order),
which meant the same insured surfaced different phone/email values
depending on which surface the user opened. A bug fix in one place
silently failed in the others.

## The contract — one-line rules

| Need | Use |
|---|---|
| Pop the Email Files dialog from anywhere | `useDeliverDocuments()({ channel: "email", ... })` |
| Pop the WhatsApp Files dialog from anywhere | `useDeliverDocuments()({ channel: "whatsapp", ... })` |
| Get the insured's email from a policy snapshot | `getDefaultEmailFromInsured(insuredSnapshot)` |
| Get the insured's mobile from a policy snapshot | `getDefaultPhoneFromInsured(insuredSnapshot)` |
| Get the insured's display name from a snapshot | `getDefaultRecipientNameFromInsured(insuredSnapshot)` |
| All three at once from `extraAttributes` | `resolveDefaultRecipientFromExtra(detail.extraAttributes)` |
| Load the PDF templates a client-share dialog should show | `usePolicyVisiblePdfTemplates(open)` |
| Filter raw `/api/pdf-templates` rows server-side | `filterPolicyVisibleTemplates(rows)` |
| Build a `wa.me` URL for a given phone + message | `buildWhatsAppUrl(phone, message)` from `@/lib/whatsapp` |
| Normalise an HK / international phone for WhatsApp | `normalizeForWhatsApp(raw)` from `@/lib/whatsapp` |

## NEVER do these

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — inline wa.me URL with hand-rolled phone cleanup
const phone = String(insured?.contactPhone ?? insured?.phone ?? "").replace(/[^0-9+]/g, "");
const url = `https://wa.me/${phone}?text=${encodeURIComponent(text)}`;
window.open(url, "_blank");

// ✅ GOOD — use the shared builder + delivery hook
import { buildWhatsAppUrl } from "@/lib/whatsapp";
import { useDeliverDocuments, getDefaultPhoneFromInsured } from "@/lib/document-delivery";

const deliver = useDeliverDocuments();
deliver({
  channel: "whatsapp",
  policyId,
  policyNumber,
  groups,                                              // see DeliveryDocGroup
  recipient: { phone: getDefaultPhoneFromInsured(insured) },
});
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — inline duplicated fallback chain
const insured = (extra.insuredSnapshot ?? {}) as Record<string, unknown>;
const candidate =
  insured.contactinfo__mobile ??
  insured.contactinfo_mobile ??
  insured.mobile ??
  // ... 5 more lines ...
  "";

// ✅ GOOD
import { resolveDefaultRecipientFromExtra } from "@/lib/document-delivery";
const { email, phone, name } = resolveDefaultRecipientFromExtra(detail.extraAttributes);
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — re-fetching + re-filtering PDF templates inline
fetch("/api/pdf-templates")
  .then(r => r.json())
  .then(rows => rows.filter(r => r.isActive && !r.meta?.isAgentTemplate /* etc */));

// ✅ GOOD
import { usePolicyVisiblePdfTemplates } from "@/lib/document-delivery";
const { templates, loading } = usePolicyVisiblePdfTemplates(dialogOpen);
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — local dialog state + inline mount
const [emailOpen, setEmailOpen] = React.useState(false);
const [waOpen, setWaOpen] = React.useState(false);
return (
  <>
    <Button onClick={() => setEmailOpen(true)}>Email</Button>
    <Button onClick={() => setWaOpen(true)}>WhatsApp</Button>
    <EmailUploadedFilesDialog open={emailOpen} onOpenChange={setEmailOpen} ... />
    <WhatsAppUploadedFilesDialog open={waOpen} onOpenChange={setWaOpen} ... />
  </>
);

// ✅ GOOD — host is mounted ONCE in the dashboard layout; just call the hook
const deliver = useDeliverDocuments();
return (
  <>
    <Button onClick={() => deliver({ channel: "email", ... })}>Email</Button>
    <Button onClick={() => deliver({ channel: "whatsapp", ... })}>WhatsApp</Button>
  </>
);
```

## How the system is wired

```
app/(dashboard)/layout.tsx
  <DocumentDeliveryProvider>
    <header>...</header>
    {children}                          ← every page reads context here
    <DocumentDeliveryHost />            ← single Email + WhatsApp dialogs
  </DocumentDeliveryProvider>
```

```
lib/document-delivery/
├── recipient.ts              # email/phone/name extraction from insured snapshot
├── pdf-templates-loader.ts   # usePolicyVisiblePdfTemplates() hook + pure filter
├── delivery-context.tsx      # DocumentDeliveryProvider + useDeliverDocuments hook
├── types.ts                  # DeliveryFile, DeliveryRecipient, DeliveryRequest
└── index.ts                  # public barrel — import everything from here

components/document-delivery/
└── DocumentDeliveryHost.tsx  # subscribes to context, mounts the right dialog
```

The two dialogs (`EmailUploadedFilesDialog`, `WhatsAppUploadedFilesDialog`)
are now controlled-only — the host owns the open/close lifecycle.

## Adding a new channel (SMS, Telegram, etc.)

1. Add the new value to `DeliveryChannel` in `lib/document-delivery/types.ts`.
2. Build a new dialog component (`SmsDeliveryDialog`, etc.) that reuses
   `usePolicyVisiblePdfTemplates` + the shared recipient helpers.
3. Render it conditionally in `DocumentDeliveryHost` based on the
   `channel` field.
4. Update this rule's "Need / Use" table.

That's it — no caller-side changes, no new context, no new fetch logic.

## Scope boundaries

- **Multi-file delivery** (Email Files / WhatsApp Files) → use `useDeliverDocuments`.
- **Single-PDF "send this template" buttons** (per-row icons in `DocumentsTab`)
  → use `useDeliverDocuments` with `groups: []` and `initialFiles: [{ kind: "pdfTemplate", id }]`.
  Pre-selects the template in the dialog so the user just clicks Send.
- **Server-to-server email** (e.g. `/api/cron/send-reminders`) → use
  `lib/email.ts` `sendEmail()` directly; this rule is for human-driven
  client surfaces.
- **Phone display** (UI only, e.g. "shown to user") → use
  `formatWhatsAppDisplay` from `@/lib/whatsapp`.

## WhatsApp Files Option A (active policy)

The codebase used to have TWO WhatsApp behaviours:

- **Old**: `wa.me?text=<rendered template text>` — recipient sees a long
  plain-text quote/invoice in chat, no file.
- **New**: `/api/policies/.../documents/share-link` mints a `/d/<token>`
  URL → recipient gets a tap-to-download link to a fresh PDF.

We intentionally chose **Option A** (file-link everywhere). The
per-row WhatsApp icons and the HTML template "WhatsApp" buttons now
both pop the share-link dialog. Customers no longer receive inline
quote/invoice TEXT in WhatsApp.

If a user wants to paste rendered text into chat manually they use
the existing **"Copy Text"** button next to "WhatsApp" in the
preview action group, then paste anywhere.

Do not regress to `wa.me?text=...` — that path is dead by design.
The tradeoff was discussed and agreed: customers gain a clean,
authoritative PDF; the seller loses inline visibility in chat (but
gains tamper-proof, auditable delivery via `document_shares`).

## Skill summary

1. Need to ship files to a person? `useDeliverDocuments()` — one call, dialog opens.
2. Need to know the recipient? `resolveDefaultRecipientFromExtra(extraAttributes)`.
3. Need PDF templates in a dialog? `usePolicyVisiblePdfTemplates(open)`.
4. Need a `wa.me` URL? `buildWhatsAppUrl(phone, msg)`.
5. Never copy-paste any of the above inline — the duplicated past was a bug factory.
